<br>
I do appreciate that there are genuine differences in the way that Americans use Her Majesty's language.  Maybe to an American, &quot;bribe&quot; means something different to what it means in the English which actual English people speak.  But in English English, &quot;bribe&quot; implies that what I'm doing is wrong or immoral and I completely reject that idea.<br>
<br>
If I discreetly or clandestinely offer someone a payment in return for them overlooking or deliberately misapplying some rule or regulation, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>that's</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> offering a bribe.<br>
<br>
If someone asks for money, and I then come out and say in front of a very wide audience how much money I'm prepared to offer and what conditions are attached to it, then that's totally <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a fucking attempted bribery.<br>
<br>
